org.gradoop.examples.keyedgrouping.functions

Class AgeRoundedTo10<E extends Attributed>

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.gradoop.examples.keyedgrouping.functions.AgeRoundedTo10<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - The type of elements to extract the key from.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, KeyFunction<E,Byte>, KeyFunctionWithDefaultValue<E,Byte>

    public class AgeRoundedTo10<E extends Attributed>
extends Object
implements KeyFunctionWithDefaultValue<E,Byte>
    A custom key-function extracting the birthday property and rounding it to the next 10.

    This key-function is extracting the property and dividing it by 10, rounding it.

    We assume that the age divided by 10 fits in a Byte value (it's range is to ).

      • addKeyToElement

        public void addKeyToElement(E element,
                            Object key)
        Store a key on an element.

        This is used to store the grouping key on the super element after grouping.

        The default implementation of this function does not change the element.

        We implement this method to store our grouping-key on super-elements. This is useful in most cases, since the user want's to know which group is represented by a super-element. In our case we multiply the key by 10, since it was divided by 10 in the getKey(Attributed) method.

        The key is stored as a property with key age_rounded, we also make sure to ignore the default key, since -10 would not be a correct age and is just used internally as the default value.

        Specified by:
        addKeyToElement in interface KeyFunction<E extends Attributed,Byte>
        Parameters:
        element - The element where the key should be stored.
        key - The key to store on the element. A Byte in this case.
